04224nam a22004815i 9780300159370DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221993ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001593707 a10.12987/97803001593702doi  a(DE-B1597)625738  a(OCoLC)1322124130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aBUS0700002bisacsh04a338.4/76887221/09731 aFormanek-Brunell, Miriam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMade to Play House :bDolls and the Commercialization of American Girlhood, 1830-1930 /cMiriam Formanek-Brunell. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2022] 4c©1993  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE The Politics of Dollhood in Nineteenth-Century America -- tCHAPTER TWO Masculinity, Technology, and the Doll Economy, 1860-1906 -- tCHAPTER THREE In the Dolls' House The Material Maternalism of Martha Chase, 1889-1914 -- tCHAPTER FOUR Marketing a Campbell Kids Culture Engendering New Kid Dolls, 1902-1914 -- tCHAPTER FIVE New Women and Talismen Rose O'Neill and the Kewpies, 1909-1914 -- tCHAPTER SIX Forging the Modern American Doll Industry, 1914-1929 -- tCHAPTER SEVEN Children's Day Constructing a Consumer Culture for Girls, 1900-1930 -- tEPILOGUE Agents or Agency Dolls in Modern America Since 1930 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDolls have long been perceived as symbols of domesticity, maternity, and materialism, designed by men and loved by girls who wanted to "play house." In this engagingly written and illustrated social history of the American doll industry, Miriam Formanek-Brunell shows that this has not always been the case. Drawing on a wide variety of contemporary sources—including popular magazines, advertising, autobiographies, juvenile literature, patents, photographs, and the dolls themselves—Formanek-Brunell traces the history of the doll industry back to its beginnings, a time when American men, women, and girls each claimed the right to construct dolls and gender.Formanek-Brunell describes how dolls and doll play changed over time: antebellum rag dolls taught sewing skills; Gilded Age fashion dolls inculcated formal social rituals; Progressive Era dolls promoted health and active play; and the realistic baby dolls of the 1920s fostered girls' maternal impulses. She discusses how the aesthetic values and business methods of women doll-makers differed from those of their male counterparts, and she describes, for example, Martha Chase, who made America's first soft, sanitary cloth dolls, and Rose O'Neill, inventor of the Kewpie doll. According to Formanek-Brunell, although American businessmen ultimately dominated the industry with dolls they marketed as symbols of an idealized feminine domesticity, businesswomen presented an alternative vision of gender for both girls and boys through a variety of dolls they manufactured themselves.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z978311053801440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030015937040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300159370423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300159370/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles